<DOC><DOCNO> AP900405-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-90 0740EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv06   04-05 0575</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 06,0597</SECOND><NOTE>$adv06</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, April 6, and Thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The heads of two major Protestant denominationssay they were outraged that heavy Panamanian civilian deaths ``werevirtually ignored by our government and media'' in connection withthe December U.S. invasion.   The Rev. Paul Sherry of the United Church of Christ and the Rev.John O. Humbert of the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)voiced their criticism in a joint letter to officials of the LatinAmerican Council of Churches.   The U.S. church leaders said they had been concerned at the``cruelty of Gen. Manuel Noriega,'' who removed from Panamanianrule in the invasion, but the churchmen added:   ``We do not support an action that represents such a flagrantviolation of national sovereignty and disregard for human life.''   The letter charged ``around 2,000 Panamanians'' were killed inthe U.S. military action. Panamanian authorities say 314Panamanians died, 202 of them civilians, and 23 Americans.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Despite the hardness of wooden pews, 42 percent ofregular church-goers in Great Britain say they sometimes fallasleep in church, a survey found.</TEXT><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Xavier University has conferred honorarydoctorates of humanities degrees on the six priests-professorsslain by military-garbed raiders last Nov. 16 at the Jesuituniversity in San Salvador.</TEXT><DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Methodist Division of HigherEducation is recommending a special emphasis on campus ministry,saying it has declined for the last 20 years but is vital to thefuture of U.S. culture.   ``Stakes are high for the church and the nation,'' a workingpaper said. It said the 1990s will bring ``several new andportentous ingredients'' to society of wide influence and that they``converge on the college campus.''</TEXT><DATELINE>GENEVA, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Lutheran World Federation reportsthat a census in Iceland found that 253,482 Icelanders _ 92.9percent of the population _ are affiliated with the EvangelicalLutheran Church of Iceland.   Roman Catholics numbered 2,367, while 3,364 declared themselvesnon-religious.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A poll of readers of the monthly U.S. Catholicfinds that most of them want Roman Catholicism to reverse its banson birth control and the ordination of women and married men.   ``After all, we know that some of the apostles were married,''wrote one reader, Lorrainie Free of Smyrna, Ga.   The majority, however, supported the church position againstabortion and premarital sex. The magazine is published by theClaretian order.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Poland's Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki saysPoland stands ready to assist in the transfer of Soviet Jews toIsrael.   Recalling that Jews in Poland have been ``an important part ofour history, tradition and culture,'' Mazowiecki told an AmericanJewish Congress dinner:   ``Just as in the Middle Ages, Poland did not evade giving helpto Jews persecuted in other countries, so today Poland will notevade humanitarian assistance to Jews emigrating from the SovietUnion.''</TEXT><DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The National Association of Evangelicals chargesthe New Age movement with ``shallow pop-psychology ofself-indulgent self-affirmation'' and ``synthetic blending of halftruths'' in a ``spiritual world that it does not understand.''   The criticisms came in a resolution at the association's annualconvention. It installed the Rev. E. Edgar Johnson, generalsecretary of the Church of the Nazarene, based in Kansas City, Mo.,as new president for a two-year term.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, April 6</NOTE></DOC>